04191nam a22005295i 9780520965577DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209655777 a10.1525/97805209655772doi  a(DE-B1597)520380  a(OCoLC)961063192  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a392/.109667223  aLB 604652rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90577:9141 aHodzic, Saida, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Twilight of Cutting :bAfrican Activism and Life after NGOs /cSaida Hodzic. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface: Coming to Questions -- tIntroduction: Governmentality against Itself -- t1. Colonial Reason, Sensibility, and the Ethnographic Style -- t2. Making Harmful Traditional Practices -- t3. When Cutting Did and Did Not End -- t4. Mistaken by Design: Biopolitics in Practice -- t5. Blood Loss and Slow Harm in Times of Scarcity -- t6. The Feminist Fetish: Legal Advocacy -- t7. Against Sovereign Violence -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tAcronyms -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe last three decades have witnessed a proliferation of nongovernmental organizations engaging in new campaigns to end the practice of female genital cutting across Africa. These campaigns have in turn spurred new institutions, discourses, and political projects, bringing about unexpected social transformations, both intended and unintended. Consequently, cutting is waning across the continent. At the same time, these endings are misrecognized and disavowed by public and scholarly discourses across the political spectrum. What does it mean to say that while cutting is ending, the Western discourse surrounding it is on the rise? And what kind of a feminist anthropology is needed in such a moment? The Twilight of Cutting examines these and other questions from the vantage point of Ghanaian feminist and reproductive health NGOs that have organized campaigns against cutting for over thirty years. The book looks at these NGOs not as solutions but as sites of "problematization." The purpose of understanding these Ghanaian campaigns, their transnational and regional encounters, and the forms of governmentality they produce is not to charge them with providing answers to the question, how do we end cutting? Instead, it is to account for their work, their historicity, the life worlds and subjectivities they engender, and the modes of reflection, imminent critique, and opposition they set in motion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520965577.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles